Distribution
============

   The Speccylator program itself may be distributed freely under the
conditions that no fee is charged above the costs of distribution and
media, and that the program is not modified in any way.

   The file @{b}Spectrum.ROM@{ub} contains an image of the 16 kByte Sinclair ZX
Spectrum ROM and it is copyright (C) Amstrad. Cliff Lawson of Amstrad
(CompuServe 75300,1517) has given special permission for emulator
authors to use the Spectrum's ROM code. (1)

   This documentation (the original Texinfo file, or any representation
generated from it) may be reproduced and distributed in any form or
processed in any way, provided no literal content, and in particular the
above copyright notices and this notice of permission, is lost in the
resulting product.

   The sample snapshot file @{b}demo.sna@{ub}, and other files included in the
original distribution of the Speccylator program which are not covered
by the above, have no restrictions whatsoever on distribution or use.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  This paragraph is basically a quote from the documentation of
@{i}Spectrum Emulator 1.7@{ui} by Peter McGavin.


@EndNode

@Node "Introduction" "Speccylator.guide/Introduction"
@Next "Usage from Workbench"
@Prev "Distribution"
@Toc "Main"

Introduction
============

   The @{i}Speccylator@{ui} is a program that emulates the Sinclair ZX Spectrum
computer. It is written for Amiga computers as an application of a
generic Z80 emulator core for the Motorola M68000 family of processors.
It is fast, completely multitasking and totally system-friendly. It
requires at least release 2.0 of the Amiga operating system, and about
435 kByte of available RAM. It requires no particular hardware beyond
that of a standard Amiga 500.

   At startup, the program attempts to load a file containing an image
of the 16 kByte Sinclair ZX Spectrum ROM. (By default, this file is
called @{b}Spectrum.ROM@{ub}. See @{"Tool Types" Link "Tool Types"}, the @{b}ROMFILE@{ub} Tool Type.) The file
included in the Speccylator distribution is copyright (C) Amstrad. See
@{"Distribution" Link "Distribution"}, for details.

   The current version (1.0) of the program emulates only the 48k model
of the ZX Spectrum. It reads and writes so-called "snapshot" project
files on the common @{b}.sna@{ub} format (see @{"Snapshot files" Link "Snapshot files"}).

   The emulator uses a custom screen for the ZX Spectrum display;
nothing else would be practical. The allocated custom screen has a
depth of 4 bitplanes and uses Lo-res resolution without interlacing.

   The program can allocate up to two audio channels, if available, for
its sound generation; at most one left channel and one right channel.
Both channels will receive the same output data.


@EndNode

@Node "Usage from Workbench" "Speccylator.guide/Usage from Workbench"
@Next "Tool Types"
@Prev "Introduction"
@Toc "Main"

Usage from Workbench
====================

   The Speccylator program can be run from the Amiga Workbench, and may
be passed a single snapshot file as argument. (See the `Amiga User's
Manual' for details about passing arguments from the Workbench and
setting Tool Type values.) Simplest, this is done by double-clicking on
the program's icon, or by similarly activating a project icon that has
the Speccylator program as its default tool.


 @{" Tool Types " Link "Tool Types"}                 The available options.

 @{" Default program settings " Link "Default program settings"}   Where and how are default settings stored?

 @{" Project settings " Link "Project settings"}           Settings for individual snapshots.


@EndNode

@Node "Tool Types" "Speccylator.guide/Tool Types"
@Next "Default program settings"
@Prev "Usage from Workbench"
@Toc "Usage from Workbench"

Tool Types
----------

   The following Tool Types affect the behaviour of the program. (Where
they exist, abbreviations are given in addition to the standard name.
However, these can only be used when running the program from the
Command Line Interface. See @{"Usage from CLI" Link "Usage from CLI"}.) Booleans can be specified
as @{b}TRUE@{ub}, @{b}YES@{ub} or @{b}ON@{ub}, and @{b}FALSE@{ub}, @{b}NO@{ub} or @{b}OFF@{ub} respectively; these keywords
are not case-dependent. If no valid right-hand value is found for a
Tool Type, its original setting is unchanged.

@{b}AUDIOCHANS@{ub}
@{b}AC@{ub}
     (@{i}String@{ui}.) @{b}BOTH@{ub}, @{b}RIGHT@{ub}, @{b}LEFT@{ub}, @{b}ANY@{ub}, @{b}NONE@{ub}, or any disjunction of
     these; e.g., @{b}RIGHT|LEFT@{ub} equals @{b}BOTH@{ub}.  @{b}BOTH@{ub} overrides @{b}LEFT@{ub} and
     @{b}RIGHT@{ub}. @{b}BOTH@{ub}, @{b}LEFT@{ub} and @{b}RIGHT@{ub} override @{b}ANY@{ub}. All of them override
     @{b}NONE@{ub}.  (Default @{b}BOTH@{ub}.)

@{b}DEBUG@{ub}
     (@{i}Boolean@{ui}.) Only available if the program was compiled with the
     compilation option @{b}DEBUG@{ub} (not in the standard distribution), this
     flag makes the program run in debugging mode, which causes the
     user interface to be handled by a separately launched process,
     while the Z80 emulation is done by the original process.  (Default
     @{b}FALSE@{ub}.)

@{b}DIRECTORY@{ub}
@{b}DIR@{ub}
     (@{i}String@{ui}.) Specifies the directory in which to look for snapshot
     files. If not given, the current directory is used.

@{b}EMULPRI@{ub}
@{b}PRI@{ub}
     (@{i}Integer@{ui}.) The priority (-128-127) of the task running the Z80
     emulation. @{i}If not specified, the spawned task runs at the same
     priority as the original process.@{ui} (The priority of the latter can
     be specified from Workbench using the standard @{b}TOOLPRI@{ub} Tool Type,
     or from CLI with the @{b}ChangeTaskPri@{ub} command.) @{i}The recommended value
     is -1 or lower.@{ui}

@{b}GAMEPORTUNIT@{ub}
@{b}GU@{ub}
     (@{i}Integer@{ui}.) Amiga game port unit number for joystick use; see the
     @{b}JOYSTICK@{ub} Tool Type.  (The default value is 1.)

@{b}INTPERIOD@{ub}
@{b}IP@{ub}
     (@{i}Integer@{ui}.) The period (a nonnegative number), in number of
     vertical blankings (50/s for PAL, 60/s for NTSC), of the maskable
     interrupt (an @{b}INT@{ub} signal). A zero value turns the periodic
     interrupt triggering off; even then, single maskable interrupts
     can still be triggered manually.  (The default value is 1.)

@{b}JOYSTICK@{ub}
@{b}JOY@{ub}
     (@{i}Boolean@{ui}.) If @{b}TRUE@{ub}, the Amiga game port selected by the
     @{b}GAMEPORTUNIT@{ub} Tool Type is activated, if it is available. (The
     default unit is 1, the normal port for joysticks; the system
     generally uses unit 0 for the mouse.) This only has effect on the
     emulation if a ZX Spectrum joystick interface (such as @{b}KEMPSTON@{ub})
     is also selected. (Default @{b}FALSE@{ub}.)

@{b}KEMPSTON@{ub}
@{b}KI@{ub}
     (@{i}Boolean@{ui}.) If @{b}TRUE@{ub}, a Kempston joystick interface attached to the
     extension port of the ZX Spectrum is emulated. If a game port on
     the Amiga is activated by the @{b}JOYSTICK@{ub} Tool Type, a joystick
     connected to that port will appear to be connected to the emulated
     interface. (Default @{b}FALSE@{ub}.)

@{b}ROMFILE@{ub}
@{b}ROM@{ub}
     (@{i}String@{ui}.) The name (relative to the current directory) of the file
     containing the 16 kByte ROM image to be read into the the ZX
     Spectrum memory at address 0 before emulation starts. If not
     specified, a file @{b}Spectrum.ROM@{ub} is searched for, first in the
     current directory and then in the directory containing the program.

@{b}SAVEICONS@{ub}
@{b}SI@{ub}
     (@{i}Boolean@{ui}.) If @{b}TRUE@{ub}, the current settings are automatically saved
     as the project's default settings when snapshots are saved, and
     icons are automatically created where none previously exist. See
     @{"Project settings" Link "Project settings"}.  (Default @{b}TRUE@{ub}.)

@{b}SCREENPERIOD@{ub}
@{b}SP@{ub}
     (@{i}Integer@{ui}.) The period (a nonnegative number), in number of
     vertical blankings (50/s for PAL, 60/s for NTSC), of the Spectrum
     screen refresh. A zero value turns the periodic screen updating
     off.  (The default value is 1.)

@{b}TITLEBAR@{ub}
@{b}TB@{ub}
     (@{i}Boolean@{ui}.) If @{b}TRUE@{ub}, the title bar of the custom screen will be
     visible.  (Default @{b}TRUE@{ub}.)

@{b}VERIFYACTIONS@{ub}
@{b}VA@{ub}
     (@{i}Boolean@{ui}.) If @{b}TRUE@{ub}, selecting any potentially harmful user action,
     like quitting the program, will first ask for verification before
     being executed.  (Default @{b}TRUE@{ub}.)

@{b}VERIFYSIGNALS@{ub}
@{b}VS@{ub}
     (@{i}Boolean@{ui}.) If @{b}TRUE@{ub}, commands to trigger processor signals like @{b}RES@{ub}
     will first ask the user for verification before being executed.
     (Default @{b}TRUE@{ub}.)


@EndNode

@Node "Default program settings" "Speccylator.guide/Default program settings"
@Next "Project settings"
@Prev "Tool Types"
@Toc "Usage from Workbench"

Default program settings
------------------------

   Default program settings are saved as Tool Types in the Speccylator
program icon (the @{b}.info@{ub} file associated with the program). If no such
file exists when defaults are saved, a new @{b}.info@{ub} file will be created,
using the built-in image for the program. If the file already existed,
only its Tool Types are affected, and of these only the ones pertaining
to the Speccylator program (see @{"Tool Types" Link "Tool Types"}) are modified.


@EndNode

@Node "Project settings" "Speccylator.guide/Project settings"
@Next "Usage from CLI"
@Prev "Default program settings"
@Toc "Usage from Workbench"

Project settings
----------------

   Settings particular to individual projects override any default
settings or settings specified on the command line. They are stored as
Tool Types in the project icon (the @{b}.info@{ub} file associated with the
project file). If no such file exists when project settings are saved,
a new @{b}.info@{ub} file will be created analogously to the case of saving
default settings.  See @{"Default program settings" Link "Default program settings"}. If the @{b}Create Icons@{ub}
menu option (see @{"The Settings menu" Link "The Settings menu"}) is turned on, project settings are
automatically saved when saving a snapshot.


@EndNode

@Node "Usage from CLI" "Speccylator.guide/Usage from CLI"
@Next "Program operation"
@Prev "Project settings"
@Toc "Main"

Usage from the Command Line Interface
=====================================

   The program has the following CLI template:

     SNAPSHOT, AC=AUDIOCHANS/K, DEBUG/S, NODEBUG/S, DIR=DIRECTORY/K,
     PRI=EMULPRI/N, GU=GAMEPORTUNIT/N, IP=INTPERIOD/N, JOY=JOYSTICK/S,
     NJOY=NOJOYSTICK/S, KI=KEMPSTON/S, NKI=NOKEMPSTON/S, ROM=ROMFILE/K,
     SI=SAVEICONS/S, NSI=NOSAVEICONS/S, SP=SCREENPERIOD/N, TB=TITLEBAR/S,
     NTB=NOTITLEBAR/S, VA=VERIFYACTIONS/S, NVA=NOVERIFYACTIONS/S,
     VS=VERIFYSIGNALS/S, NVS=NOVERIFYSIGNALS/S

   Most options have abbreviations, and every boolean option has a
corresponding negated form, whose name is @{b}NO@{ub} (or @{b}N@{ub} for the
abbreviations) appended with the name of the positive form. The negated
and abbreviated forms can only be used when running from the CLI. See
@{"Tool Types" Link "Tool Types"}, for descriptions of the effects of these options.

   Options specified on the command line override any default settings.
For instance, entering:

     Speccylator JetPac.sna PRI -1 AC ANY JOYSTICK NTB KEMPSTON

the Speccylator would attempt to load a snapshot (project) file named
@{b}JetPac.sna@{ub}, and execute with Z80 emulation task priority -1, allocating
a single audio channel, the joystick enabled (in the default joystick
port), the titlebar hidden, and Kempston interface emulated. (This is
unless the CLI options are overridden by project settings. See
@{"Project settings" Link "Project settings"}.)


@EndNode

