@EndNode

@Node "The Project menu" "Speccylator.guide/The Project menu"
@Next "The Settings menu"
@Prev "Program operation"
@Toc "Program operation"

The Project menu
................

@{b}Open Snapshot...@{ub}
     Opens a file requester for selecting a project snapshot file to be
     loaded.  If the @{b}DIRECTORY@{ub} Tool Type (see @{"Tool Types" Link "Tool Types"}) has been
     specified, the requester will show that directory (if it exists);
     otherwise, the program's current directory is shown.

@{b}Save Snapshot...@{ub}
     Like @{b}Open Snapshot...@{ub}, but a Save requester is opened instead. The
     Z80 emulation is automatically halted during the whole of the
     operation. If the @{b}Create Icons@{ub} menu option is turned on (see
     @{"The Settings menu" Link "The Settings menu"}), the current settings are automatically saved
     in the project icon file. See @{"Project settings" Link "Project settings"}.

@{b}Reload Project@{ub}
     Reloads the current project, without reloading settings.

@{b}Save Screen...@{ub}
     Opens a Save requester for writing the current contents of the
     screen to a file, in IFF ILBM format. The Z80 emulation is
     automatically halted during the whole of the operation. No icon is
     created for the image file.

@{b}Save Settings@{ub}
     Saves the current settings as the project's default settings. See
     @{"Project settings" Link "Project settings"}.

@{b}Reload Settings@{ub}
     Loads settings from the project's icon file (if it exists).

@{b}Save Defaults@{ub}
     Saves the current settings as the defaults. See
     @{"Default program settings" Link "Default program settings"}.

@{b}Reload Defaults@{ub}
     Loads settings from the program's icon file (if it exists).

@{b}Quit@{ub}
     Terminates the Speccylator program.


@EndNode

@Node "The Settings menu" "Speccylator.guide/The Settings menu"
@Next "The Emulation menu"
@Prev "The Project menu"
@Toc "Program operation"

The Settings menu
.................

@{b}Title Bar@{ub}
     If turned on, the title bar of the custom screen is visible. See
     @{"Tool Types" Link "Tool Types"}, the @{b}TITLEBAR@{ub} Tool Type.

@{b}Create Icons@{ub}
     If turned on, the current settings are automatically saved as the
     project's default settings when a snapshot is saved, and new
     project icons are created where none already exist. See
     @{"Project settings" Link "Project settings"}. Also @{"Tool Types" Link "Tool Types"}, the @{b}SAVEICONS@{ub} Tool Type.

@{b}Verifications@{ub}
     If turned on, the program asks for verification before executing
     any potentially harmful user action. See @{"Tool Types" Link "Tool Types"}, the
     @{b}VERIFYACTIONS@{ub} Tool Type.

@{b}Audio@{ub}
     Selects the audio channels to be used (if available): @{b}Both@{ub}, @{b}Right@{ub},
     @{b}Left@{ub}, @{b}Any@{ub} (a single channel) or @{b}No Audio@{ub}.  The @{b}No Audio@{ub} submenu
     item can be toggled, in which case the setting prior to the first
     selection is restored. See @{"Tool Types" Link "Tool Types"}, the @{b}AUDIOCHANS@{ub} Tool Type.

@{b}Screen Updating@{ub}
     Sets the refresh frequency of the ZX Spectrum screen, in percent
     of the vertical blanking frequency (50 Hz for PAL, 60 Hz for
     NTSC), or turns it off completely. The @{b}Off@{ub} submenu item can be
     toggled, in which case the setting prior to the first selection is
     restored. Values other than those in the submenu can be set using
     the @{b}SCREENPERIOD@{ub} Tool Type. See @{"Tool Types" Link "Tool Types"}.

@{b}Task Priority@{ub}
     Sets the priority of the task running the Z80 emulation. Values
     other than those in the submenu can be set using the @{b}EMULPRI@{ub} Tool
     Type.  See @{"Tool Types" Link "Tool Types"}.


@EndNode

@Node "The Emulation menu" "Speccylator.guide/The Emulation menu"
@Next "The Processor menu"
@Prev "The Settings menu"
@Toc "Program operation"

The Emulation menu
..................

@{b}Pause@{ub}
     When selected, all emulation (processor, interrupts, screen
     updating, etc.) is halted. When deselected, everything is turned
     on again. All functions are affected, even if some have been
     individually enabled or disabled.

@{b}Joystick@{ub}
     If turned on, the Amiga game port selected by the @{b}GAMEPORTUNIT@{ub} Tool
     Type is activated, if it is available. (Default unit is 1, the
     normal joystick port.) See @{"Tool Types" Link "Tool Types"}, the @{b}JOYSTICK@{ub} Tool Type.

@{b}INT Frequency@{ub}
     Sets the frequency of the periodic maskable interrupt signal, in
     percent of the vertical blanking frequency (50 Hz for PAL, 60 Hz
     for NTSC), or turns it off completely. The @{b}Off@{ub} submenu item can be
     toggled, in which case the setting prior to the first selection is
     restored. Values other than those in the submenu can be set using
     the @{b}INTPERIOD@{ub} Tool Type.  See @{"Tool Types" Link "Tool Types"}.

@{b}Interfaces@{ub}
    @{b}Kempston@{ub}
          If turned on, a Kempston joystick interface attached to the
          extension port of the ZX Spectrum is emulated. If a game port
          on the Amiga is activated (see the @{b}Joystick@{ub} menu option
          above), a joystick connected to that port will appear to be
          connected to the emulated interface. See @{"Tool Types" Link "Tool Types"}, the
          @{b}KEMPSTON@{ub} Tool Type.


@EndNode

@Node "The Processor menu" "Speccylator.guide/The Processor menu"
@Next "Keyboard layout"
@Prev "The Emulation menu"
@Toc "Program operation"

The Processor menu
..................

@{b}Halt@{ub}
     If turned on, the Z80 emulation is halted (but other functions of
     the emulation remain unaffected).

@{b}Verifications@{ub}
     If turned on, the program asks for verification before executing
     any command to trigger a processor signal, like @{b}RES@{ub}.

@{b}INT@{ub}
     Triggers the Z80's @{b}INT@{ub} (maskable interrupt) signal.

@{b}NMI@{ub}
     Triggers the Z80's @{b}NMI@{ub} (nonmaskable interrupt) signal.

@{b}RES@{ub}
     Triggers the Z80's @{b}RES@{ub} (reset) signal.


@EndNode

@Node "Keyboard layout" "Speccylator.guide/Keyboard layout"
@Next "Snapshot files"
@Prev "The Processor menu"
@Toc "Main"

Keyboard layout
***************

   The basic correspondence between the Amiga keyboard and that of the
ZX Spectrum is simple: the alphanumerical Amiga keys (@{b}A@{ub}-@{b}Z@{ub} and @{b}0@{ub}-@{b}9@{ub}) map
directly to the same keys on the ZX Spectrum keyboard, and the Space
bar to the Spectrum's Space key.

   Both Shift keys map to the Spectrum's Caps Shift key, and both Alt
keys to the Symbol Shift key. When the Amiga Caps Lock is activated,
the effect is that of keeping the Spectrum's Caps Shift key pressed
down; when Caps Lock is turned off again, it corresponds to releasing
Caps Shift.

   The Numeric pad works similarly; Enter maps to the Spectrum's Enter
key, and the keys @{b}0@{ub}-@{b}9@{ub} map to the corresponding Spectrum keys.

   The Help key, the function keys (@{b}F1@{ub}-@{b}F10@{ub}), the Ctrl key and the two
Amiga keys have no effect on the ZX Spectrum keyboard emulation.

   All remaining keys are mapped to sequences of keypresses on the ZX
Spectrum keyboard, rather than to particular keys or symbols. Some of
them can be modified by holding down a Shift key, but not all. The keys
are interpreted according to the standard American keyboard (since it
seems likely that most people are more or less familiar with that
layout), and produce keypress sequences that yield the corresponding
symbol or effect if initiated in the normal editing mode of the ZX
Spectrum BASIC line editor.

   In particular, the following keys are of interest:

   @{b}*@{ub} Esc: Go into @{i}E-mode@{ui}.

   @{b}*@{ub} Back Space and Del: Delete (Caps Shift + @{b}0@{ub}).

   @{b}*@{ub} Left Arrow, Down Arrow, Up Arrow and Right Arrow: Cursor keys
     (Caps Shift + @{b}5@{ub}, @{b}6@{ub}, @{b}7@{ub} and @{b}8@{ub}, respectively).


@EndNode

@Node "Snapshot files" "Speccylator.guide/Snapshot files"
@Prev "Keyboard layout"
@Toc "Main"

Snapshot files
**************

   A @{i}snapshot file@{ui} is a complete machine state dump of a 48 kByte
Sinclair ZX Spectrum - the RAM memory contents and the processor state.
The format is also called the Mirage Microdrive format, after the piece
of hardware from which it originates.

   Snapshot file names are usually suffixed with @{b}.sna@{ub} or @{b}.snapshot@{ub}. A
publicly available program named @{i}spconv@{ui}, written by Henk de Groot, can
be used to convert such files to and from other snapshot formats, such
as the common @{b}.Z80@{ub} format.

The snapshot format
-------------------

   A snapshot reflects the state of the machine after the occurrence of
a non-maskable interrupt. Thus, the 2 bytes on top of the stack (the
address pointed to by the saved stack pointer, and the next higher
address) form the address to which the program counter was pointing
when the interrupt occurred - this is always the address of the
instruction which was to be executed next. The lower stack address
contains the least significant byte (bits 0-7) of the program counter,
and the higher address the most significant byte (bits 8-15); this is
how 16-bit words are always handled in the Z80.

   The first 27 bytes of the snapshot file hold the saved processor and
hardware state, at the following offsets (16-bit registers stored with
the least significant byte first; for e.g. the register pair @{b}HL@{ub}, this is
the 8-bit register @{b}L@{ub}):

     Offset  Name  Comment
     
      0:     I     (8-bit register)
      1:     H'L'  (16-bit register pair)
      3:     D'E'  (16-bit register pair)
      5:     B'C'  (16-bit register pair)
      7:     A'F'  (16-bit register pair)
      9:     HL    (16-bit register pair)
     11:     DE    (16-bit register pair)
     13:     BC    (16-bit register pair)
     15:     IY    (16-bit register)
     17:     IX    (16-bit register)
     19:     ---   (8 bits): Bit 2 set if maskable interrupts are enabled.
     20:     R     (8-bit register)
     21:     AF    (16-bit register)
     23:     SP    (16-bit register): The stack pointer
     25:     ---   (8 bits): Interrupt mode: 0, 1 or 2.
     26:     ---   (8 bits): Border colour (0-7) in bits 0-2.

   Directly after this (at offset 27 from the start of the file) follow
the contents of the 48 kByte RAM (located at addresses 16384-65535) of
the machine at the time the nonmaskable interrupt occurred.

@EndNode

